:"1371–Overleden","1296–Male":"1296–Overleden","1315–Female":"1315–Overleden","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1351":"1351","1296":"1296","1371":"1371","1370":"1370","Uckfield, East Sussex, Sussex, England":"Uckfield, Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Hendall Manor, Uckfield, Sussex, England":"Uckfield, Sussex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1351–":"1351–Deceased","1351–Female":"1351–Deceased","1346–Male":"1346–Deceased","1371–Female":"1371–Deceased","1296–Male":"1296–Deceased","1315–Female":"1315–Deceased","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1351":"1351","1296":"1296","1371":"1371","1370":"1370","Uckfield, East Sussex, Sussex, England":"Uckfield, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","Hendall Manor, Uckfield, Sussex, England":"Uckfield, Sussex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Walsh","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Aileen, Dermot, John Patrick, Kieran, Declan, Eamonn, Colm, Donal, Seamus, Siobhan, Brennan.","English and Irish: ethnic name from Middle English <i>walshe</i> (Old English <i>wælisc</i>) ‘foreign, Welsh’. This form of the name was generally more common than   Welsh  , especially in Ireland, where it originally denoted a Welsh-speaking immigrant, in particular any of the Welshmen who arrived in the wake of Strongbow's Anglo-Norman invasion of 1170. In Ireland it is sometimes also a translation of <b>Breathnach</b> ‘Briton’.","English: in Yorkshire and Lancashire the name is sometimes a shortened form of   Walshaw  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Walshe","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Irish Brendan, Eoin, Murph.","English and Irish: variant of   Walsh  ."]},{"name":"McBratney","meanings":["Scottish: Anglicized form of Gaelic <b>Mac Breatnaigh</b> ‘son of the Briton’ (referring to the Welsh of Strathclyde). Compare   Walsh   and   Galbraith  ."]},{"name":"Welsh","meanings":["Scottish, English, and Irish: ethnic name from Middle English <i>welshe</i> (Old English <i>wēalisc</i>, <i>wēlisc</i>) ‘foreign, Welsh’, for someone from Wales or a speaker of the Welsh language. Compare   Walsh   and   Wallace  .","Americanized form of German   Welsch  .","Americanized form of Ukrainian and Jewish (from Ukraine)   Voloshin   or its Polish variant <b>Wołoszyn</b> (see   Woloszyn  )."]}]},{"name":"Joan","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Contracted form of Old French <i>Jo(h)anne</i>, from Latin <i>Io(h)anna</i> (  see  Joanna  ). In England this was the usual feminine form of   John   from the Middle English period onwards and was extremely popular, but in the 16th and 17th centuries it steadily lost ground to   Jane .  It was strongly revived in the first part of the 20th century, partly under the influence of  George Bernard Shaw's  play St Joan (  1923 ), based on the life of  Joan of Arc  (  1412–31 ). Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Lady Joan Walsh was born in 1351, in Uckfield, Sussex, England, United Kingdom, her father, Thomas Walsh, was 55 and her mother, Mrs. Thomas Walsh, was 36. She married Sir. John de Hindedale in 1370, in Uckfield, Sussex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 daughter."},"et":{"1351–":"1351–Surnud","1351–Female":"1351–Surnud","1346–Male":"1346–Surnud","1371–Female":"1371–Surnud","1296–Male":"1296–Surnud","1315–Female":"1315–Surnud","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1351":"1351","1296":"1296","1371":"1371","1370":"1370","Uckfield, East Sussex, Sussex, England":"Uckfield, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Hendall Manor, Uckfield, Sussex, England":"Uckfield, Sussex, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1351–":"1351–Kuollut","1351–Female":"1351–Kuollut","1346–Male":"1346–Kuollut","1371–Female":"1371–Kuollut","1296–Male":"1296–Kuollut","1315–Female":"1315–Kuollut","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1351":"1351","1296":"1296","1371":"1371","1370":"1370","Uckfield, East Sussex, Sussex, England":"Uckfield, Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Hendall Manor, Uckfield, Sussex, England":"Uckfield, Sussex, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"1351–":"1351–Décédée","1351–Female":"1351–Décédée","1346–Male":"1346–Décédé","1371–Female":"1371–Décédée","1296–Male":"1296–Décédé","1315–Female":"1315–Décédée","1315":"1315","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","1351":"1351","1296":"1296","1371":"1371","1370":"1370","Uckfield, East Sussex, Sussex, England":"Uckfield, Sussex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","Hendall Manor, Uckfield, Sussex, England":"Uckfield, Sussex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Lorsque Lady Joan Walsh est née en 1351, à Uckfield, Sussex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni, son père, Thomas Walsh, avait 55 ans et sa mère, Mrs. Thomas Walsh, avait 36 ans. Elle a épousé Sir. John de Hindedale en 1370, à Uckfield, Sussex, Angleterre, Royaume-Uni. Ils ont eu au moins 1 fille."},"de":{"13